[1] Cholera - Haiti
Date: Mon 13 Oct 2014
Source: Design and Trend [edited]
http://www.designntrend.com/articles/21513/20141013/amidst-ebola-outbreak-cholera-remains-problem-haiti.htm


The World Bank pledged USD 50 million to the battle against cholera in Haiti Thursday, 9 Oct 2014. World Bank officials hope to further the Haitian initiative to maintain clean water, improve sanitation and better health. The bank announced the donation at a conference and called for other donors, according to Outbreak News. With the donations, Haitian people will potentially gain access to safe water, which will slow the growth of waterborne diseases, like cholera.

"We have made significant progress in controlling the cholera epidemic in Haiti, but too many people are still getting sick, mainly because they don't have access to clean water and lack sanitation systems. Cholera remains endemic and water-borne diseases are one of the leading causes of infant mortality in Haiti," said Jim Yong Kim, World Bank Group President. "Expanding coverage of safe water and sanitation is possible. We cannot ignore this opportunity to prevent thousands more Haitian children from dying from waterborne diseases," added Kim.

"I fear that the enormous progress we have made leads people to believe that the problem has been resolved. It is not resolved," Pedro Medrano, the UN coordinator overseeing cholera response in Haiti, told AFP.

Since the beginning of the cholera epidemic, which began in October 2010, 8562 people have died. There have been 703 510 reported cases and 393 912 of those with the disease were hospitalized.

While the number of cholera deaths has decreased since the outbreak began 4 years ago, Haiti is still averaging 291 cases and 1 death each week in 2014.

[Byline: Amanda Stewart]

